<div id="review_4080388258" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4080388258" />
    <a title="Michelle Victora" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/16635782-michelle-victora"><img alt="Michelle Victora" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1589466896p2/16635782.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4080388258?book_show_action=true">Jul 25, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Michelle Victora" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Michelle Victora" href="/user/show/16635782-michelle-victora">Michelle Victora</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4080388258" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3943403768219352901">I&apos;m obviously not able to say I really really liked this or anything &apos;cause I&apos;m... not Christian. BUT I appreciate that Martin Luther managed to appropriately address financial exploitation led by the church and in doing so, he empowered a lot of people to take control of their own faith and therefor their own life. As an agnostic (but mostly an atheist) I always have a hard time understanding the buy-in involved in ultra-dominant monotheistic religion. Like, if the only thing you need is faith </span>
  <span id="freeText3943403768219352901" style="display:none">I'm obviously not able to say I really really liked this or anything 'cause I'm... not Christian. BUT I appreciate that Martin Luther managed to appropriately address financial exploitation led by the church and in doing so, he empowered a lot of people to take control of their own faith and therefor their own life. As an agnostic (but mostly an atheist) I always have a hard time understanding the buy-in involved in ultra-dominant monotheistic religion. Like, if the only thing you need is faith but faith is the most important thing, where is the room for healthy skepticism and doubt (seems like there's no room, right?) But even if I'm not sure I believe in God, I can identify with some of the values in this text, such as... be a good person, do good works, but don't derive meaning from the good works themselves, first make sure you have the right intentions. Well, it's confusing, I guess I also believe good works can make you a good person and of course, what does it mean to be "good" if you don't have religion, but golden rules good enough for me and I'm figuring the rest of it all out as I go along.<br /><br />What's crazy to me is how much power Martin Luther had. Definitely see him as a positive influence and his note the pope at the end of the book was a very bold, confident mix of reverence and advice-giving that I couldn't imagine giving to such a big-deal authority figure.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3943403768219352901" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

<tr class="no_border feedFooterReview" id="update_comment_stuff_Review4080388258">
